Disable SSH Root Login (Linux)
Secure your server - prevent direct root SSH login.

Step 1: Edit SSH Config
bash
sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config
Find & change:

text
#PermitRootLogin yes
PermitRootLogin no
Save: Ctrl+O, Enter, Ctrl+X

Step 2: Restart SSH Service
bash
# Ubuntu/Debian
sudo systemctl restart ssh

# CentOS/RHEL
sudo systemctl restart sshd
Step 3: Verify Changes
bash
# Check service status
sudo systemctl status ssh

# Confirm config
sudo sshd -T | grep permitrootlogin
# Output: permitrootlogin no
Step 4: Test Root Lockout
bash
# From another machine
ssh root@your_server_ip
# Expected: Permission denied (publickey)/Access denied!
Quick Commands
bash
sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config           # Edit config
# Change: PermitRootLogin no

sudo systemctl restart ssh              # Restart service
sudo sshd -T | grep permitrootlogin     # Verify: "no"
ssh root@server_ip                      # Test: Denied!

Status Check
Command	Expected Output
systemctl status ssh	          active (running)
sshd -T | grep permitrootlogin	permitrootlogin no
ssh root@ip	                    Permission denied

Security Benefits:
✅ Prevents root brute-force attacks
✅ Forces sudo usage (logged)
✅ Uses regular user + sudo

Troubleshooting
text
❌ "sshd: unrecognized service"
✅ Use: sudo systemctl restart sshd (RHEL/CentOS)

❌ Config changes not applied
✅ Restart SSH + verify with sshd -T
